ðŸ”¹ Problem 1: Logistic Regression (Classification)


from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix

# Sample dataset
X = [[25, 50000], [40, 60000], [30, 40000], [35, 52000]]
y = [1, 1, 0, 1]

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=1
)

# Train model
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Prediction
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluation
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Confusion Matrix:\n", confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))


ðŸ”¹ Problem 2: Linear Regression (Prediction)

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Sample dataset
X = [[1000], [1500], [2000], [2500]]
y = [50, 75, 100, 125]

# Train model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Prediction
pred = model.predict([[1800]])

# Evaluation
print("Predicted Price:", pred)
print("MSE:", mean_squared_error(y, model.predict(X)))



ðŸŽ¤ Viva One-Liners

Logistic Regression? â†’ Classification

Linear Regression? â†’ Prediction

Train-test split? â†’ Model evaluation

Accuracy? â†’ Correct predictions

